# Real-Time Notification Rules (Socket.IO)

## Architecture

- Socket.IO server attached to the Express HTTP server in `src/server.ts`.
- Stored on `app.set('io', io)` -- retrieved in controllers via `req.app.get('io')`.
- Clients authenticate with JWT via `socket.handshake.auth.token`.

## Room Conventions

| Room | Pattern | Purpose |
|------|---------|---------|
| User room | `user_${userId}` | Targeted notifications (new WO assigned, comment added) |
| WO room | `wo_${woId}` | Real-time comment feed on a specific work order |

Clients auto-join their `user_${userId}` room on connection.
Clients manually join WO rooms via `join_wo_room` socket event.

## Notification Service (`src/services/notification.service.ts`)

Class + singleton pattern:
```typescript
class NotificationService {
    async notifyCommentAdded(params: CommentNotificationParams): Promise<void> {
        const { workOrder, commenter, io } = params;
        // 1. Determine recipients (assignee + requester, excluding commenter)
        // 2. For each recipient:
        //    a. Create Notification DB record
        //    b. Emit: io.to(`user_${targetUserId}`).emit('new_notification', data)
        // 3. Errors caught and logged, never thrown (fire-and-forget)
    }
}
export const notificationService = new NotificationService();
```

## Usage from Controller

```typescript
// In controller method:
const io = req.app.get('io');
await workOrderService.addComment(woId, orgId, dto, audit, io);

// In service:
notificationService.notifyCommentAdded({ workOrder, commenter, io });
```

## Socket.IO Events

### Server -> Client
- `new_notification` -- new notification for the user
- `new_comment` -- new comment on a WO the user is viewing (broadcast to `wo_${woId}` room)

### Client -> Server
- `join_wo_room` -- join a specific work order room for live comments
- `leave_wo_room` -- leave a work order room

## Error Handling

- NotificationService methods are **fire-and-forget**. Errors are caught and logged via Pino, never thrown.
- Notification DB creation failures do not block the primary operation (e.g., adding a comment).
- Socket.IO emit failures are silently logged.

## Notification DB Table

Table: `notifications`
- `id` (UUID PK)
- `user_id` (UUID FK) -- recipient
- `title` (STRING) -- notification title
- `message` (TEXT) -- notification body
- `is_read` (BOOLEAN, default false)
- `link` (STRING, nullable) -- deep link (e.g., `/work-orders/uuid`)
- `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at` (paranoid)
